## {#multiple-logistic-slide data-menu-title="Multiple logistic regression"}

[Multiple logistic regression]{.slide-title}

<hr>

The logistic model extends naturally to multiple predictors $X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_p$:

$$p(X) = \frac{e^{\beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p}}{1 + e^{\beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p}}.$$

The log-odds remain **linear in all predictors**:

$$\log\left(\frac{p(X)}{1 - p(X)}\right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p.$$

. . .

Each coefficient $\hat\beta_j$ represents the change in log-odds for a one-unit increase in $X_j$, **holding all other predictors constant**:

::: {.body-text-s}
- $\hat\beta_j > 0$: increasing $X_j$ $\Rightarrow$ higher log-odds $\Rightarrow$ higher $p(X)$ (holding other predictors fixed)
- $\hat\beta_j < 0$: increasing $X_j$ $\Rightarrow$ lower log-odds $\Rightarrow$ lower $p(X)$ (holding other predictors fixed)

<!-- **Note:** raw coefficients are in different units (°C vs. μmol/L here), so their magnitudes are not directly comparable for assessing "which predictor matters more." -->
:::

